ds mainly due to the high altitude. Acute Mountain Sickness (AMS) is a frequent problem in the Himalayan region and can affect a traveler is various ways irrespective of their age, gender or health fitness. Even if you are in perfect health and peak fitness, you can still develop AMS. Previous experience of high places, pre-ascent training and good physical shape do not prevent the onset of altitude sickness - it can strike anyone of any age. Our body normally time to be acclimated to the high altitude. The body undergoes a number of physiological changes some of which are increased pulse and respiratory rate. Others appear slowly over a period of weeks like the change in acid base balance and production of extra red blood cells. These changes and the effect of intense sunlight, strenuous walks and dehydration may cause some mild or vague symptoms such as:<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Loss of appetite<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Fatigue<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Headache<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Nausea<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Dizziness<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Palpitations<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Sleeplessness<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Breathlessness<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;The condition is caused by lower than normal levels of oxygen being absorbed. If the sickness is acute, you can become confused, irrational and mentally unbalanced. The best way to counter it is prevention. You should not exert yourself or walk too fast. Drinking plenty of liquid, eating well and watching for warning sign is highly advised. Aside from following your guide&#39;s advice, you can try to eat a diet that is high in carbohydrates to build up glycogen in the muscles, avoid unnecessary vigorous activity in addition to the trek or climb and do not ascend faster than you need. Keep physical activity to the minimum and take regular doses of diamox as directed by your physician. IF the symptoms do not recede then do not hesitate to talk with our staff. Our trekking teams carry a Gamow bag (a portable compression chamber) to be used in severe cases. If you have a history of respiratory and heart problem please consult your physician before embarking on this trip. But based on our years of experience, with proper preparation and time taken to acclimatize, severe cases are relatively rare. Though we will ensure that you are safe and at worst will suffer only the mildest of symptoms it is best to listen to your body; no-one knows it better than you!&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nVaccination<br />\r\nImmunisations currently recommended for Nepal are those for Hepatitis A and Typhoid. Ensure also that you apply insect repellent liberally and do not expose bare skin to mosquitoes after dusk. Meningitis is a risk in certain areas of Nepal at certain times of year and you should consult your doctor as to whether immunisation is necessary.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPhysical fitness<br />\r\nSince the above trip entails traveling at high altitude it is necessary that the client is in good health. Before you embark on any one of these trips it is advisable to be physically and mentally fit and prepared. Prepare yourself by jogging or walking at least one hour daily for a minimum period of one month. A thorough health check up is strongly recommended before the trip.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMedical Facilities<br />\r\nThere are many pharmacies which sells medicines and some have a doctor&rsquo;s clinic. Prescription is not a requirement for purchase of harmless drugs in Nepal.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nInsurance<br />\r\nInsurance All the clients are strongly advised to have personal travel insurance covering trip cancellations or interruptions due to natural disasters or medical reasons, insurance against emergency evacuation, medical and accident insurance. You will need to leave your insurance details in our office in Kathmandu during the trip so that we can make necessary arrangements should the need arise.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRisk and Liability&nbsp;<br />\r\nOur trips mean safety, reliability and the professional personnel to ensure your convenience at all times. However sometimes unforeseen circumstances like landslides, floods, bad weather, bad road condition, vehicle breakdown, delay in flights due to bad weather, local political situation could contribute to the change in the program. No claim of refund will be entertained including early return from the trip, or change in itinerary due to unavoidable situations like the above. All extra expenses (apart from the services offered as per the program) that occur in such cases would have to borne directly by the clients themselves.</p>\r\n','<p>Day&nbsp;1&nbsp;Drive Kathmandu - Borderlands or The Last Resort (1170) 4 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;2&nbsp;The Last Resort/Borderlands (1170 m) - Listi (2260 m) 5 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;3&nbsp;Listi (2260 m) - Shotang Kharka (3379 m) 7 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;4&nbsp;Shotang Kharka (3379 m) - Chogomogor Kharka (3925 m) 5-6 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;5&nbsp;Chogomogor Kharka (3925 m) - Kyansin (2520 m) 5 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;6&nbsp;Kyansin (2520 m) - Tembathang (2160 m) 5 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;7&nbsp;Tembathang (2160 m) - Chedupa Kharka (2513 m) 7 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;8&nbsp;Chedupa Kharka (2513 m) - Nemagchukpa kharka (3578 m) 5 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;9&nbsp;Nemagchukpa kharka (3578 m) - Panch Pokhari (4074 m) 5 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;10&nbsp;Panch Pokhari (4074 m). Rest day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;11&nbsp;Panch Pokhari (4074 m) - Intermediary Camp (4273 m) 4 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;12&nbsp;Intermediary Camp (4273 m) - Tin Pokhari (4255 m) 4 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;13&nbsp;Tin Pokhari (4255 m) - High South Camp (4867 m) 5 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;14&nbsp;High South Camp (4867 m) - High North Camp (4720m) via Tilman pass (5308m) 8 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;15&nbsp;High North Camp (4720m) - Kyanjin Gomba (3830m) 7 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;16&nbsp;Kyangjin Gompa (3830 m) 7 hrs. Rest day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;17&nbsp;Kyangjin Gompa (3830 m) - Ghora Tabela (3030 m) 6 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;18&nbsp;Ghora Tabela (3030 m) - Syabru Besi (1503m) 6 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;19&nbsp;Syabru Besi (1503 m) - Kathmandu by bus (8 hrs)</p>\r\n','<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Please inquire for a custom quote. The price is customized based on final hotel choices, travel dates, and other custom preferences.</span></p>\r\n','','2017-01-23 13:55:12','admin','2017-07-18 05:46:45','admin'),
(72,'EVEREST TO ROLWALING TREK','KHUMBU ','everest-to-rolwaling-trek','[\"61\",\"71\"]','everest-to-rolwaling-trek1485162360.jpg','28 days','0',12,'','','','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Rolw?ling Him?l</strong>&nbsp;(<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nepali_language\" title=\"Nepali language\">Nepali</a>:&nbsp;?????????? ?????), (Rolwaling Valley), knows as a (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaurishankar\" title=\"Gaurishankar\">Gaurishankar</a>) VDC is a section of the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Himalayas\" title=\"Himalayas\">Himalayas</a>&nbsp;in east-central Nepal along the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tibet\" title=\"Tibet\">Tibet</a>&nbsp;border.&nbsp;<sup><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rolwaling_Himal#cite_note-carter1985-2\">[2]</a></sup>&nbsp;Rolwaling Himal includes&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melungtse\" title=\"Melungtse\">Melungtse</a>&nbsp;7181m and Melungtse II 7023m inside Tibet and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaurishankar\" title=\"Gaurishankar\">Gaurishankar</a>&nbsp;7134m on the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nepal\" title=\"Nepal\">Nepal</a>&nbsp;border with some 50 additional peaks over 6000m, all extending from the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nangpa_La\" title=\"Nangpa La\">Nangpa La</a>&nbsp;pass where the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahalangur_Himal\" title=\"Mahalangur Himal\">Mahalangur</a>&nbsp;section begins, southwest to the Tamakosi River. The&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Labuche_Kang\" title=\"Labuche Kang\">Labuche</a>&nbsp;Himal section rises beyond the Tamakosi to the northwest. Rolwaling Himal is bounded on the south by the Rolwaling Valley which contain several small&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sherpa_(people)\" title=\"Sherpa (people)\">sherpa&#39;s villages</a>, the largest town in the area. It would take five to six days to reach&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Namche_Bazaar\" title=\"Namche Bazaar\">Namche Bazaar</a>&nbsp;after pass Tasilapcha. You also can trek to Everest base camp or you can trek to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lukla\" title=\"Lukla\">Lukla</a>&nbsp;and fly to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kathmandu\" title=\"Kathmandu\">Kathmandu</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">source :&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rolwaling_Himal\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rolwaling_Himal</a></p>\r\n','<p>Please enquire at Khumbila support team.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','<p>Day&nbsp;1&nbsp;Flight Kathmandu - Lukla (2840 m); trek to Phakding (2610 m) 5 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;2&nbsp;Phakding (2610 m) - Namche Bazaar (3450 m) 6 hrs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;3&nbsp;Namche Bazaar (3450 m). Acclimatization day. Optional trek to Khumjung and Khunde village (4-5 hrs)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;4&nbsp;Namche Bazaar (3450 m) - Tengboche (3860 m) 5 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;5&nbsp;Tengboche (3860 m) - Dingboche (4410 m) 5 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;6&nbsp;Dingboche (4410 m). Rest day. Optional trek to Chhukung Ri (5500 m) 7-8 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;7&nbsp;Dingboche (4410 m) - Lobuche (4910 m) 4 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;8&nbsp;Lobuche (4910 m) - Gorak Shep (5140 m) afternoon visit to Everest Base Camp (5360 m) 7 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;9&nbsp;Gorak Shep (5140 m) - Morning visit to Kala Patthar (5550 m) - Trek to Lobuche (4910 m) 6 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;10&nbsp;Lobuche (4910 m) - Dzongla (4830 m) 5 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;11&nbsp;Dzongla (4830 m) - Dragnag (4700 m) via Cho-La pass (5420 m) 7 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;12&nbsp;Dragnag (4700 m) - Gokyo Lake (4750 m) 3 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;13&nbsp;Gokyo Lake (4750 m). Rest day. Climb Gokyo Ri (5360 m) for views of Everest and Cho Oyu. Round trip 3 hrs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;14&nbsp;Gokyo Lake (4750 m) - Lumde (4380 m) via Renjo-La Pass (5360 m) 7-8 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;15&nbsp;Lumde (4380 m) - Thame (3820 m) 4 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;16&nbsp;Thame (3820 m) - Pachemuche Tsho (4780 m) 6 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;17&nbsp;Pachemuche Tsho (4780 m) - Ngole (5110 m) 3 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;18&nbsp;Ngole (5110 m) - Tashi Labsta Camp (5665 m) 3 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;19&nbsp;Tashi Labsta Camp (5665 m) - Glacier Camp (4735 m) via Tashi Labsta-La pass (5755 m) 8-9 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;20&nbsp;Glacier Camp (4735 m) - Na Gaon (4180 m) 7 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;21&nbsp;Na Gaon (4180 m) - Dokhang (2791 m) 7 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;22&nbsp;Dokhang (2791 m) - Simigaon (2036 m) 5 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;23&nbsp;Simigaon (2036 m) - Bulungse (2000 m) 7-8 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;24&nbsp;Bulungse (2000 m) - Loting (1768 m) 6 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;25&nbsp;Loting (1768 m) - Bigu Gompa (2516 m) 5 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;26&nbsp;Bigu Gompa (2516 m) - Sano Jyandan (3127 m) via Tinsang-La pass (3798 m) 7 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;27&nbsp;Sano Jyandan (3127 m) - Borderlands or The Last Resort (1170 m) 6 hrs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Day&nbsp;28&nbsp;Drive to Kathmandu by bus (4 hrs)</p>\r\n','<p>Please inquire for a custom quote. The price is customized based on final hotel choices, travel dates, and other custom preferences.</p>\r\n','0','2017-01-23 14:51:00','admin','2017-07-18 05:46:52',''),
